05952nam a22006975i 9780822397083DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223970837 a10.1515/97808223970832doi  a(DE-B1597)551971  a(OCoLC)1229161224  a(OCoLC)1125856757  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3507b.J36 1995 7aMUS0250002bisacsh04a781.65/0900aJazz Among the Discourses /cKrin Gabbard. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b7 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Jazz Canon and Its Consequences -- tRETHINKING JAZZ HISTORY -- t"Moldy Figs" and Modernists: Jazz at War (I942-I946) -- tJazz in Crisis, I948-I958: Ideology and Representation -- tOther: From Noun to Verb -- tHistorical Context and the Definition of Jazz: Putting More of the History in "Jazz History" -- tOral Histories of Jazz Musicians: The NEA Transcripts as Texts in Context -- tThe Media of Memory: The Seductive Menace of Records in Jazz History -- tTHE JAZZ ARTIST AMONG THE DISCOURSES -- t"Out of Notes": Signification, Interpretation, and the Problem of Miles Davis -- tCritical Alchemy; Anthony Braxton and the Imagined Tradition -- tEphemera Underscored: Writing Around Free Improvisation -- tTHE ESSENTIAL COM TEXT: JAZZ AND POLITICS -- tDouble V; Double-Time: Bebop's Politics of Style -- tAscension: Music and the Black Arts Movement -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of jazz comes of age with this anthology. One of the first books to consider jazz outside of established critical modes, Jazz Among the Discourses brings together scholars from an array of disciplines to question and revise conventional methods of writing and thinking about jazz.Challenging "official jazz histories," the contributors to this volume view jazz through the lenses of comparative literature; African American studies; music, film, and communication theory; English literature; American studies; history; and philosophy. With uncommon rigor and imagination, their essays probe the influence of various discourses-journalism, scholarship, politics, oral history, and entertainment-on writing about jazz. Employing modes of criticism and theory that have transformed study in the humanities, they address questions seldom if ever raised in jazz writing: What are the implications of building jazz history around the medium of the phonograph record? Why did jazz writers first make the claim that jazz is an art? How is an African American aesthetic articulated through the music? What are the consequences of the interaction between the critic and the jazz artist? How does the improvising artist navigate between chaos and discipline?Along with its companion volume, Representing Jazz, this versatile anthology marks the arrival of jazz studies as a mature, intellectually independent discipline. Its rethinking of conventional jazz discourse will further strengthen the position of jazz studies within the academy.Contributors. John Corbett, Steven B. Elworth, Krin Gabbard, Bernard Gendron, William Howland Kenney, Eric Lott, Nathaniel Mackey, Burton Peretti, Ronald M. Radano, Jed Rasula, Lorenzo Thomas, Robert Walser  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aJazzxHistory and criticism. 0aMusical canon. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh1 aGendron, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeretti, Burton W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLott, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbard, Krin, e